WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.026
And as men, we've got to look for ways for us to bond together and to be able to do that.

00:04.166 --> 00:15.924
So our final charge, Matthew chapter 24, verse 14 says, in this gospel of the kingdom shall be preached in all the world as a witness and then shall the end come.

00:17.226 --> 00:22.654
And this gospel of the kingdom shall be preached in all the world for a witness and then shall the end come.

00:22.714 --> 00:24.937
So we'll do our final charge.

00:24.957 --> 00:27.140
Father God, we thank you for this opportunity to study a word.

00:27.160 --> 00:28.242
We thank you for your

00:28.674 --> 00:37.648
Your love, Lord, your kindness, and for the opportunity to fellowship with brethren today like we did, it has really just been such a blessing, Lord, our hearts are overflowing.

00:38.570 --> 00:41.234
Lord, we want to leave with a word from you.

00:42.316 --> 00:43.958
This is our prayer in Jesus' name.

00:44.419 --> 00:44.800
Amen.

00:46.222 --> 00:49.507
So the Apostle Paul clearly understood sports.

00:50.108 --> 00:51.370
A lot of Adventists don't like sports.

00:51.491 --> 00:51.951
I get that.

00:52.632 --> 00:54.636
But clearly Paul understood sports.

00:54.816 --> 00:56.178
He writes about sports.

00:56.354 --> 00:59.018
And the sporting event of his day was the Olympics.

00:59.619 --> 01:11.097
And what would happen in the Greek Olympics is that they would, as a young man, you could go to Athens to the Olympics, represent your village, and you could go there and win a prize.

01:11.718 --> 01:12.419
They had a few things.

01:12.439 --> 01:14.662
They had wrestling, Greco-Roman wrestling to this day.

01:15.063 --> 01:15.884
They had boxing.

01:16.064 --> 01:17.486
They had sprinting.

01:17.506 --> 01:18.448
They'd race each other.

01:18.468 --> 01:19.930
What else?

01:21.112 --> 01:21.773
They had a marathon.

01:21.793 --> 01:22.394
That was the 26th year.

01:22.434 --> 01:23.616
That's what a marathon comes from.

01:23.636 --> 01:25.138
So they had these events.

01:25.314 --> 01:28.258
And if you won, you went home to your village a hero.

01:29.260 --> 01:34.848
So young men, like today, they would train for years to be able to go to the Olympics.

01:34.868 --> 01:36.871
The Apostle Paul understood that.

01:37.552 --> 01:38.794
It was a huge thing.

01:38.814 --> 01:40.977
It was a major focus.

01:41.999 --> 01:50.592
And so he writes in 1 Corinthians chapter 9 and verse 24, he writes, know ye that, know ye not that they would run in a race, run all.

01:50.632 --> 01:51.353
How many of them run?

01:52.214 --> 01:54.738
Everybody that lines up in a race is running to win the race.

01:55.458 --> 01:58.562
He says, but only one of them receives the prize.

01:59.644 --> 02:02.187
He says, so run that you may obtain.

02:03.048 --> 02:03.910
Here's what he's saying.

02:03.950 --> 02:07.615
Do not run the Christian race haphazardly.

02:08.576 --> 02:11.240
Don't run the Christian race like you really don't want to win.

02:11.280 --> 02:15.626
Don't line up and get in, set in the blocks and get in position.

02:16.046 --> 02:21.153
And when the gun goes off, you just mosey and along to the finish line like you ain't got no sense.

02:22.295 --> 02:24.498
Paul says, take the race

02:24.610 --> 02:27.074
the Christian race seriously.

02:28.896 --> 02:35.586
On judgment day, when we stand before God, he's gonna look at us and we can say, Lord, you know what, I didn't run the race that well.

02:35.786 --> 02:37.309
He said, why didn't you?

02:38.290 --> 02:43.217
Everything you needed to run this race and win this race, I gave it to you.

02:44.519 --> 02:46.322
You say, no, Lord, I didn't have this in this.

02:46.362 --> 02:49.326
He'll hold up his nail scarred hands.

02:50.849 --> 02:51.730
Let's go verse 25.

02:53.186 --> 02:58.352
And every man that strives for the mastery is temperate in all things.

02:59.053 --> 03:03.719
Now they do it to obtain a corruptible crown, but we an incorruptible.

03:04.881 --> 03:06.683
These temperate, meaning they're self-controlled.

03:07.023 --> 03:08.826
That means they don't do things other people do.

03:08.846 --> 03:10.327
They don't go places other people go.

03:10.347 --> 03:11.889
They don't wear things other people wear.

03:12.090 --> 03:14.433
They don't eat or drink things other people eat their temperate.

03:14.453 --> 03:16.615
My cousin, I mentioned my cousin Sean Taylor.

03:16.635 --> 03:22.002
Sean, when we were little kids, and I'm older than Sean, but when Sean was like,

03:22.338 --> 03:50.226
seven or eight six seven eight years old Sean would actually climb up on the side of the couch he'd be on the arm of the couch and as you walk by he would jump off the couch and try and tackle you he did something about it he just liked to hit people from he was a little kid so his parents at both at Venice they weren't together but he were both at Venice and so he would go to he was going to church

03:50.594 --> 04:16.690
his father realized how good he was in father and p his father was also the the uh... chief of police for florida city florida p pulled him out would take him from church to play pop water football in miami and charmed was like a man among boys it was crazy i never want this game there are seven but they come back and say this guy scored four touchdown five times he had half the tackles i mean he was just

04:16.770 --> 04:21.716
a man among boys as it looked like from pop Warner days, right?

04:22.596 --> 04:33.629
Now, what was interesting about him is he went on and he played for one of the public high schools before he got drafted over to play in a private high school, right?

04:34.049 --> 04:37.693
And the private high school is the same private high school where Madonna sent her kids.

04:38.494 --> 04:41.938
So it's Gulliver Prep, you can look it up, really elite high school.

04:42.306 --> 04:47.733
They won their first state championship with Sean Taylor playing both ways, Ironman football.

04:48.594 --> 04:50.336
They won their first state championship.

04:51.377 --> 04:52.318
It went crazy.

04:53.059 --> 04:58.065
What I learned from Sean, and I have another cousin who played in the NFL, my cousin Keith Rieser.

04:58.085 --> 05:04.092
He played for San Francisco, and he won a football, actually, with Patrick Mahomes in Kansas City.

05:04.913 --> 05:08.818
What I learned from watching Sean is he was temperate.

05:09.442 --> 05:15.891
His father would take him outside, but he was just, you know, middle school, and he would have him running up and down the street.

05:15.931 --> 05:17.894
He has a revelation chapter three, and I think it's verse 11.

05:19.215 --> 05:25.544
Speaking to one of the churches, Jesus actually says, be careful lest another man take your crown.

05:25.564 --> 05:28.128
Oh, there it is.

05:29.149 --> 05:34.537
Your crown exists, but somebody else can take it.

05:34.557 --> 05:38.482
I want you to run the race understanding you want it already.

05:40.098 --> 05:44.162
The job is to submit to the one who gives you strength to win the race.

05:46.164 --> 05:50.429
You can't run the race and think you are the one running.

05:50.729 --> 05:55.954
You've got to understand that the wind that is pushing you forward is the wind of the glory of God.

05:59.278 --> 06:07.026
Now, I want to give a little bit more info on my cousin, because it fits into this.

06:08.738 --> 06:11.521
So Sean was doing very well.

06:11.561 --> 06:17.407
Many of you know he got recruited first, but a University of Miami in Florida, my alma mater.

06:17.907 --> 06:24.333
And they won a national championship his first year at a Rose Bowl up in Pasadena.

06:26.535 --> 06:28.397
And within a year or two, I forgot many years now.

06:28.457 --> 06:30.199
He left football.

06:30.219 --> 06:31.580
I remember him asking me one off season.

06:31.600 --> 06:33.883
He's like, Ricky, he'll answer my family.

06:33.903 --> 06:36.665
He said, I should stay in college or should I go?

06:36.685 --> 06:37.266
And I was like,

06:37.442 --> 06:38.924
Most of us go to college to get a job.

06:39.865 --> 06:41.827
I said, you got a really good job.

06:41.927 --> 06:46.733
So I would probably go get the money while you were still young enough to go get it.

06:47.214 --> 06:49.056
Sure enough, he came out early out of college.

06:49.396 --> 06:52.220
And some of you might remember if you die hard Redskins fans.

06:52.700 --> 06:55.284
He went number five in the NFL draft.

06:55.304 --> 06:55.804
Do you remember that?

06:56.926 --> 07:03.954
He signed a $36 million contract when he came out of college.

07:04.578 --> 07:33.938
His agent was Drew Rosenhouse, y'all remember him, he's the one they made the movie show me the money, I wasn't even in that movie again, Derek Maguire, he's the one who made, that's what that movie is about, I sat, I actually met him, I was able to meet him, but Sean signed that there's, and one of the things that was interesting is you signed a $36 million contract, people change, your family will change, everything changes, people see you as a resource,

07:34.114 --> 07:35.035
more than anything else.

07:35.496 --> 07:39.041
$36 million kind of came to the Washington Redskins and was doing well.

07:39.061 --> 07:42.666
And you guys that really follow football remember he got in trouble.

07:43.648 --> 07:47.313
Remember somebody stole, he was an outdoors guy, was an outdoorsman.

07:47.894 --> 07:56.306
Fisherman, he didn't really hunt but he fished and he loved to go out into the Everglades in Florida on his four wheel ATV Banshees I think they call them.

07:56.386 --> 07:57.547
I don't really mess with that kind of stuff.

07:57.567 --> 07:59.970
But he was out in the Everglades all the time on him.

08:00.030 --> 08:10.421
And the mistake he made is he took the Banshees and left them at one of our friends' houses back in our old neighborhood, which was a big mistake.

08:10.461 --> 08:13.264
It wasn't a very good neighborhood, Perrine in Miami, right?

08:14.125 --> 08:17.509
And so some of the dudes from the hood stole his Banshees.

08:18.410 --> 08:22.194
I think it was four of them, at least two or three of them, but I think it was four of them.

08:22.306 --> 08:26.191
Stolen Banshees and Sean, being Sean, Sean did not take shorts.

08:26.732 --> 08:29.395
He's not the kind of dude you mess around with.

08:29.775 --> 08:38.106
So he took his gun and went to the dude's houses in the hood, drew his gun, and at gunpoint got back all of his stolen stuff.

08:39.728 --> 08:41.029
Now, what do you think the guys did?

08:42.051 --> 08:43.052
They called the police.

08:43.833 --> 08:44.554
They snitched.

08:44.594 --> 08:47.858
They broke every rule of the hood, right?

08:48.226 --> 08:49.648
First thing they did was stitch.

08:50.389 --> 08:52.812
So they called the police because they knew who he was.

08:53.733 --> 08:55.135
Again, he didn't realize it.

08:55.315 --> 08:56.236
He didn't realize.

08:56.256 --> 08:59.540
When you saw a $36 million contract, you didn't even see it.

08:59.560 --> 09:02.424
He was supposed to drive through the hood no more.

09:02.785 --> 09:05.929
You need to stay where you stay because you are liability.

09:06.089 --> 09:07.250
You're vulnerable.

09:07.731 --> 09:08.512
They call the police.

09:08.572 --> 09:09.754
Sean gets in trouble.

09:09.774 --> 09:10.575
Some of y'all remember this.

09:11.275 --> 09:12.517
And Sean was all in the news.

09:12.557 --> 09:14.079
They were painting him as this bad person.

09:14.139 --> 09:16.402
They were calling him all this kind of stuff.

09:17.250 --> 09:23.059
And my grandmother, my Jamaican grandmother from Betheltown, Jamaica, prayed him out of this mess.

09:24.681 --> 09:26.123
But he had to give up his guns.

09:26.203 --> 09:27.425
His dogs were getting loose.

09:28.006 --> 09:29.188
He had to give up his dogs.

09:30.149 --> 09:32.492
And so he had this really nice house by now.

09:32.933 --> 09:36.699
And in that off season, after all that happened, his girlfriend had had a baby.

09:36.759 --> 09:38.662
And Sean quickly began to change.

09:38.742 --> 09:43.669
In fact, this is a picture from when I saw him at one of our cousin's baby showers.

09:43.809 --> 09:45.532
We were at a cousin, one of my cousin's baby showers.

09:45.912 --> 09:47.154
And Sean and I were talking.

09:47.586 --> 09:53.393
And just before they took this picture, we were talking, and Sean told me, Sean, turn to me, and he said, I'm tired of the NFL.

09:54.354 --> 09:56.077
He said, Rick, you don't really understand.

09:56.097 --> 09:58.600
He said, the owners don't really care for the fans.

09:58.900 --> 10:00.142
They don't really care for the players.

10:00.182 --> 10:01.383
It's just a business, he said.

10:01.844 --> 10:06.069
He said, as soon as this is over, he said, I'm going back to church.

10:06.089 --> 10:07.090
I was like, whoa.

10:08.052 --> 10:08.933
He said, I'm going back to church.

10:08.953 --> 10:11.696
And in that off season, he actually went to church.

10:13.759 --> 10:16.402
And when the appeal was made, he came down front.

10:17.954 --> 10:25.481
Now, somebody allowed, I won't say who, somebody allowed some people into the house that they shouldn't have.

10:25.501 --> 10:34.330
And he was away in Virginia, here in Virginia, you know, in training camp or whatever, you know, in the football season, early in the football season.

10:34.590 --> 10:38.074
And these guys were invited over to his house, should never have been in his house.

10:38.734 --> 10:39.315
I wanted to it.

10:39.355 --> 10:41.597
And when they looked around, they saw his jewelry laying around.

10:42.218 --> 10:43.919
They saw his game checks laying around.

10:44.280 --> 10:45.361
Sean was just that type of dude.

10:45.401 --> 10:46.802
None of that stuff really mattered to him.

10:47.394 --> 10:50.558
So all this stuff was just laying around, and they said, well, we'll just wait till he's not home.

10:51.339 --> 10:52.460
We'll break into the house.

10:53.201 --> 10:54.523
And we can steal all this stuff.

10:54.543 --> 10:57.066
It's the easiest money we'll ever make.

10:57.907 --> 10:59.649
There came from the other side of the state.

11:00.750 --> 11:02.352
Sean didn't even know these dudes, really.

11:02.412 --> 11:08.600
I mean, one of them, they said he actually did help out, actually, one time, because these boys knew some people we knew.

11:09.401 --> 11:15.028
Anyway, Sean, the Redskins played the Tampa Bay Buccaneers in Tampa.

11:15.048 --> 11:16.690
And Sean had heard his name.

11:16.962 --> 11:19.445
After that off season, that way he was doing really well.

11:19.565 --> 11:21.007
Lots of tackles, interceptions.

11:21.407 --> 11:22.909
He was having a stellar season.

11:24.010 --> 11:27.694
But he hurt his knee, so he was in Tampa, and he asked the coach, who was the coach then again?

11:28.195 --> 11:28.675
Was it Gibbs?

11:29.236 --> 11:29.716
Gibbs, yeah.

11:30.057 --> 11:31.979
So he asked Gibbs could he go, so he said he had to go home.

11:31.999 --> 11:45.394
So Sean went back to Miami from Tampa, a short little trip, check him on his fishing boat, because he loved the fish, check him on his car, check him on his house, you know, visit some relatives, hang out with a baby and his girlfriend, you know, with the families,

11:46.434 --> 11:49.939
And while they were sleeping in the house, those boys came back for the stuff.

11:51.381 --> 11:52.682
Four of them.

11:52.702 --> 11:55.326
They drove all the way from the other coast of the state of Florida.

11:56.948 --> 12:00.253
And Sean, you know, they didn't have an alarm on his house.

12:01.214 --> 12:02.375
You were $36 million.

12:02.416 --> 12:04.759
You should have Ironman alarm on your house.

12:06.621 --> 12:06.842
Right?

12:06.882 --> 12:07.683
Dogs, everything.

12:08.684 --> 12:09.625
Cameras, everything.

12:09.846 --> 12:16.114
And so the dudes went around the back of the house and came in through the back window of the bathroom.

12:16.994 --> 12:20.377
Sean heard them coming in, being the child of Jamaicans.

12:21.859 --> 12:23.820
He drew out a machete because he had no gun no more.

12:24.621 --> 12:26.103
Went with his cut list and went outside.

12:26.163 --> 12:31.668
One of the two boys that went in, from what we understand, only one of them had a gun.

12:32.549 --> 12:37.453
And he probably, I don't know what the boy really wanted to do what he did in a final analysis.

12:37.794 --> 12:43.179
He shot, and it seems like he shot at Sean's leg, hit him in the left thigh.

12:43.219 --> 12:46.802
The problem is the bullet went through Sean's femoral artery.

12:47.138 --> 12:49.180
That's the biggest, you know, anatomy.

12:49.200 --> 12:51.142
It's the biggest artery of the lower extremities.

12:51.643 --> 12:53.084
Sean is a world-class athlete.

12:53.204 --> 12:54.145
His adrenaline is running.

12:54.165 --> 12:55.387
His heart is pumping super fast.

12:55.747 --> 12:59.851
He is pushing blood out of that artery at a rapid, rapid pace.

13:00.973 --> 13:04.316
His father told me later on that he thinks all of Sean's blood was left at the house.

13:05.858 --> 13:07.960
His girlfriend and the baby are hiding in the closet.

13:08.000 --> 13:08.981
She hears the gunshot.

13:09.281 --> 13:13.746
So, of course, she doesn't come out because, you know, who was the risk of the baby getting shot.

13:14.210 --> 13:21.161
So she stays in the closet, and when she finally does come out and call 911, he's laying there unconscious in a giant pool of blood.

13:22.043 --> 13:26.330
They rush him to the University of Miami Hospital Jackson Memorial, right at Trauma Center.

13:26.991 --> 13:33.682
They give him $60,000 worth of albumin, a protein to keep the blood in his vessels, pump of albumin fluid,

13:33.826 --> 13:37.532
And Sean is laying there in the whole world, CNN, ESPN.

13:37.873 --> 13:38.935
I'm watching it from Cali.

13:38.955 --> 13:40.096
I'm in Loma Linda working.

13:40.397 --> 13:41.599
I'm watching my family.

13:41.619 --> 13:43.743
I'm watching my cousins come and go from the hospital.

13:43.763 --> 13:45.165
ESPN and CNN give updates.

13:45.485 --> 13:48.010
Sitting at the hospital, worried about my family, praying.

13:48.030 --> 13:49.753
I've never forget my brother called me that night.

13:50.314 --> 13:55.202
When Sean was shot, it was like 10 o'clock at night on the West Coast.

13:55.222 --> 13:56.584
And he says, Sean has been shot.

13:58.006 --> 13:58.968
I said, how does it look?

13:58.988 --> 14:00.210
And he was like, not good.

14:00.546 --> 14:11.160
I remember falling on my knees in my house in California and begging God to let him live because we already lost so many family members to murder and unnecessary deaths.

14:13.544 --> 14:14.465
Sean is laying there now.

14:15.266 --> 14:17.689
My Jamaican grandmother comes on the scene.

14:18.611 --> 14:23.878
She comes in and she sits next to him as they wouldn't even take him out of the operating room because it was a VIP.

14:24.198 --> 14:25.640
It was like the safest place to leave him.

14:26.281 --> 14:29.906
So he's laying in there, they're giving him fluids, they're doing everything, they're monitoring him.

14:30.114 --> 14:36.862
My grandmother takes the chair, pulls up next to the bed, sits where her face is right next to his ear, and she begins to hum and sing.

14:38.204 --> 14:39.926
She then begins to recite words.

14:41.187 --> 14:43.691
She's talking to him, then she'll go back into song.

14:44.031 --> 14:45.593
This goes on for hours.

14:48.837 --> 14:51.440
My brother says, he talks to my grandmother, we call her mama.

14:51.660 --> 14:53.583
My brother says, mama, do you want to go home?

14:53.623 --> 14:55.565
I can take you home to shower and change and come back.

14:55.585 --> 14:57.607
Mama's like, nah, I'm not going home.

14:57.668 --> 14:59.730
She stays there singing, praying, everything.

15:00.450 --> 15:02.733
Two days, two and a half days into this.

15:02.793 --> 15:04.595
He's still there trying to recover.

15:06.718 --> 15:07.699
My grandmother's sitting there.

15:08.820 --> 15:13.466
And my grandmother, the key is, we were all raised in broken homes and stuff.

15:13.486 --> 15:16.910
So the one repository for all of us was my grandmother's house.

15:16.930 --> 15:21.656
Like when my mother wanted to get rid of all three of us boys, we all went to my grandmother's house, right?

15:21.776 --> 15:23.659
So we all, she part raised all of us.

15:25.000 --> 15:26.002
So she's there doing that.

15:26.022 --> 15:28.685
My brother is like, she's not moving.

15:28.705 --> 15:29.586
She won't go anywhere.

15:30.338 --> 15:33.702
Finally, two and a half days in, the doctor and the nurse walk in.

15:35.343 --> 15:39.368
When the doctor and the nurse walk in, the doctor says to the nurse, hold his hand.

15:39.428 --> 15:41.610
The nurse grabs my cousin's hand.

15:42.131 --> 15:46.275
And the doctor says, Shawn, if you can hear me, squeeze her hand.

15:46.736 --> 15:47.537
And he squeezes.

15:49.319 --> 15:52.302
The doctor says, Shawn, if you can hear me, blink.

15:53.183 --> 15:54.304
And he blinks his eyes.

15:55.886 --> 15:59.730
The nurse looks at the nurse, the nurse looks at the doctor, they shrug his shoulders, and they walk off.

16:00.706 --> 16:06.312
When they walk out of the room, my grandmother gets up, turns to my brother and says, OK, I'm ready to go shower now.

16:06.332 --> 16:07.153
My brother said, what do you mean?

16:07.193 --> 16:08.534
Like, it seems like stuff is happening.

16:08.554 --> 16:09.536
She said, no, no, it's time to go.

16:09.556 --> 16:10.216
Let me go shower.

16:10.857 --> 16:11.498
She goes to shower.

16:11.518 --> 16:12.779
I'm watching a news in California.

16:12.799 --> 16:14.060
My brother tells me what's happened.

16:14.080 --> 16:16.203
I'm watching news in California, ESPN, CNN.

16:16.543 --> 16:17.985
Sean Taylor responds to doctors.

16:18.285 --> 16:19.626
We think he might make a recovery.

16:19.927 --> 16:20.928
Everyone's hopes are up.

16:21.248 --> 16:22.509
My brother's like, he doesn't look good.

16:22.530 --> 16:23.611
I don't know how this going to happen.

16:24.392 --> 16:29.117
And everybody, you know, the news is saying it's going to happen within a day, day and a half.

16:29.157 --> 16:30.418
I remember how hours it was.

16:30.850 --> 16:31.371
He dies.

16:34.434 --> 16:42.044
I go, I fly down for the funeral, but one of my sons, we fly down to the funeral, and I make a beeline for my grandmother.

16:43.205 --> 16:45.328
I say, mama, this doesn't make sense.

16:45.348 --> 16:52.137
You were praying, praying for him, there with him, and as soon as he seemed like he was going to get better, you went home.

16:54.019 --> 16:57.924
She said, listen, I was there with him for all those days, all those hours.

16:57.944 --> 16:59.666
She said, I was reteaching him.

16:59.874 --> 17:01.558
the Sabbath school lessons.

17:01.578 --> 17:03.062
I used to teach him when he was a child.

17:05.107 --> 17:07.853
He was an acquirer, he was a pathfinder, Sean Taylor, all that.

17:08.876 --> 17:14.930
He was singing in his ear, the songs used to sing him as a little boy for worship on Friday evening.

17:15.554 --> 17:21.021
She was reciting Bible verses and Bible promises and teach and reminding him of what the gospel teaches.

17:21.262 --> 17:23.304
She said, but Ricky, I started to get tired.

17:23.585 --> 17:24.246
I was dirty.

17:24.386 --> 17:24.987
I was hungry.

17:25.227 --> 17:26.008
I wanted to go home.

17:26.048 --> 17:26.629
So I prayed.

17:26.669 --> 17:30.174
I said, God, if he can hear me, show me that he can hear me.

17:30.915 --> 17:33.518
She said, when she prayed that prayer, the doctor and the nurse walked in.

17:35.381 --> 17:39.586
She said, once I knew he could hear me, I knew my work was done.

17:39.646 --> 17:45.234
She said, it was time to go home and prepare for his funeral.

17:50.434 --> 17:53.758
We tell you something.

17:53.778 --> 17:55.119
At that funeral, it was a circus.

17:56.120 --> 17:56.401
O.J.

17:56.421 --> 17:57.082
Simpson was there.

17:59.064 --> 18:03.349
Chad Ocho-Sinko, almost a whole entire Redskins organization.

18:04.070 --> 18:06.672
Holy University of Miami's football apparatus was there.

18:07.493 --> 18:12.819
Many other NFL players, because we grew up in a section of Miami, we grew up in a lot of football players come out of NFL players come out of that area.

18:14.501 --> 18:18.546
And I'll never be in that to be in that funeral, and people politicizing his death and all of this.

18:19.266 --> 18:21.229
This is his tombstone there in Miami.

18:22.270 --> 18:28.959
Right near my mother's, right near my grandmother's, right near my grandfather's in my aunt's, all in one plot, they all are there in Kendall and Florida.

18:30.501 --> 18:34.487
And I'll never forget, everybody was all into it until they weren't.

18:35.909 --> 18:39.594
Finally, everybody trickled away and it was time for his body to go down into the ground.

18:40.275 --> 18:41.717
And this thing to go on top of it.

18:43.018 --> 18:48.626
By now, all the celebrities, all the other football players go on, there's just a few of us family members and a few of us friends from our neighborhood.

18:51.106 --> 19:00.856
We were crying bitterly, not because he played for the Redskins, but because he wasn't coming back.

19:00.876 --> 19:05.560
The Redskins, I said, when I give one of his talks for the funeral, I said the Redskins are going to have another safety next year.

19:06.441 --> 19:08.303
I'm not going to have another cousin to take his place.

19:09.924 --> 19:11.045
The Redskins are going to move on.

19:11.065 --> 19:11.426
They did.

19:11.706 --> 19:12.547
They even changed their name.

19:16.170 --> 19:19.794
But what I want to tell you ties into everything I talked about today,

19:21.826 --> 19:27.653
When it came time to bury him, his cars, BMW, all that, was still in the driveway at the house.

19:28.855 --> 19:31.658
That big mansion of a house he bought for how much money?

19:32.660 --> 19:33.861
It was still on his foundation.

19:34.682 --> 19:42.051
That beautiful, amazingly massive fishing boat thing he had, still sitting there in the driveway.

19:42.933 --> 19:46.777
His jewelry, all of it was 99% of it was still at the house.

19:47.558 --> 19:50.482
Whatever of that $36 million went into his bank account,

19:51.554 --> 20:08.434
still in the bank when Sean died and went into the grave the only thing he could take with him of any value is if he went down with Christ the only thing you get to take to heaven with you is your character

20:09.314 --> 20:12.399
I'm so glad in and off season he took his stand when he had the opportunity.

20:12.859 --> 20:17.867
I'm so glad that before he lost consciousness completely and forever, my grandmother was able to witness to him.

20:18.207 --> 20:24.076
And my prayer is that one day when I receive my crown by God's grace, I get to see him receive his.

20:25.659 --> 20:30.406
Men, what we are fighting for the race we are in, we do not run like other men run.

20:30.466 --> 20:33.330
There's a crown waiting for us.

20:33.634 --> 20:36.338
So we beat down our body and bring it into subjection.

20:36.679 --> 20:39.243
Let's after all that we've been through.

20:40.785 --> 20:43.429
We should be called a cast away.

20:45.052 --> 20:47.315
Men leave this place on fire for God.

20:48.357 --> 20:49.719
What his brother said is so important.

20:50.140 --> 20:52.083
Don't just go home to a men's ministry.

20:52.343 --> 20:55.268
Go home and have a men's ministry that thrives.

20:56.069 --> 21:01.938
Go home and ask yourselves, what can we do as men in this church so that the women are no longer the priests

21:02.082 --> 21:04.546
The time of this talk was supposed to be King Priest or Coward.

21:05.407 --> 21:06.990
Let's go home and be priests.

21:08.652 --> 21:10.976
If you're married, be a priest in your home.

21:11.016 --> 21:16.304
Let your instruction be the primary instruction about God your children get.

21:16.865 --> 21:22.113
If you think a pastor's gonna raise your child to be Christian, you've already lost your child.

21:23.976 --> 21:25.258
That has to happen at home.

21:25.298 --> 21:30.546
Be a king to the queen your wife, for those of us who are married.

21:31.010 --> 21:38.580
make sure that we treat them as Christ treats the church, the way he treats the church is the way we're supposed to treat our wife.

21:38.880 --> 21:41.223
How many of us have that attitude with our wives?

21:43.566 --> 21:44.567
And you know why he says he does it?

21:45.388 --> 21:56.442
So he can present us a glorified church, Ephesians 5, 25, 26 and 27, without spot, without wrinkle, without any sort of blemish.

21:58.245 --> 21:59.346
Let me tell you something.

22:00.066 --> 22:01.869
is the reality all of us have to face.

22:02.450 --> 22:04.473
We talk a lot about how soon Jesus is coming and we should.

22:05.394 --> 22:12.044
But let me tell you something, I know for in fact, all of us are one day going to have to stand before the judgment seat of the living God.

22:13.266 --> 22:21.058
Right now is when you prepare for that day because I want to be wearing the robe of Christ's righteousness when that happens.

22:21.559 --> 22:29.170
When my name comes up in the judgment, I want the screen to go blood red as the universe looks at me and Jesus say,

22:29.282 --> 22:31.885
He has been covered by my righteousness.

22:32.846 --> 22:33.486
That's what you want.

22:33.506 --> 22:36.129
Just stand with me as we close out in prayer.

